article.description:
Eric Musselman got fed up with his team's
free-throw woes this week, and started requiring extra shots before
practice.
article.headline: Golden State hits 31 of 33 FTs to beat Toronto
article.linkText: Free throw shooting practice pays off for Warriors
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Eric Musselman got fed up with his team's free-throw woes this week, and started requiring extra shots before practice. It seems to be paying off. Earl Boykins made all six of his foul shots in the final 30 seconds and Golden State converted 31 of 33 attempts in a 101-96 victory over the Toronto Raptors on Friday night. Boykins, the Warriors' 5-foot-5 sparkplug off the bench, scored his team's final 10 points over the last 3:40 to finish with 16. ''It was big down the stretch to hit free throws,'' Boykins said. ''I just go out there and play hard. That's my main goal. I just want to be consistent.'' Troy Murphy had 19 points and a career-high 16 rebounds, and Gilbert Arenas had 22 points, eight rebounds and six assists as the Warriors snapped a two-game losing streak and sent the Raptors to their fifth consecutive defeat and ninth in 10 games. Erick Dampier added 16 points and eight rebounds. Golden State had lost seven of nine. ''These were two teams desperate for a win,'' Musselman said. Boykins was 8-for-8 from the line and Murphy, who sustained a mild concussion in the defeat Sunday at Sacramento, made all seven of his attempts. Boykins is the new fan favorite, and received a standing ovation. ''The fans have been big to me here,'' said Boykins, who signed with Golden State late last month. ''They're very supportive and I appreciate it.'' Voshon Lenard and Alvin Williams each scored 17 to lead six players in double figures for Toronto, but Lenard missed four key free throws down the stretch. Toronto shot 16-for-24 from the line. ''We missed a lot of free throws, but we need to make a lot of them,'' coach Lenny Wilkens said. ''It wasn't just Voshon.'' Arenas scored four consecutive points for Golden State to tie it at 84 with 7:10 left. Jason Richardson made an acrobatic move to score and get fouled with 5:48 left, converting his free throw for an 89-86 lead. Lenard missed two free throws at 4:59 and Antawn Jamison followed with a powerful dunk on the other end to make it 91-86. The Raptors called time out and the Warriors received a standing ovation from the crowd of 16,487. Toronto went on an 8-0 run late in the third quarter to go ahead 77-72, but Boykins kept the Warriors in it with four points in the final 56 seconds to pull Golden State to 77-76 down heading into the fourth. Toronto again played without Vince Carter and Antonio Davis. Carter, who has played in just 10 games this season and has been out since early December with a knee injury, did not travel with the team for the game Thursday at Seattle. Davis, who has been sidelined since Dec. 6 with a swollen right knee, also stayed behind in Toronto. Toronto's Jelani McCoy was whistled for his fifth foul with 8:39 left in the third, then called for a technical as he complained about the call as he took a seat on the bench. After returning in the fourth, he quickly picked up his sixth foul with 8:10 left. McCoy was held to 11 points, only two in the second half. The Raptors used an 11-1 run in the second quarter to go ahead by six, but couldn't hold their lead. Murphy scored nine in a row -- including two monstrous dunks -- as the Warriors built a 58-52 halftime lead. Jerome Williams began the game defending Murphy, but was out during Murphy's second-quarter spurt. Toronto jumped out to an early 19-10 lead but cooled off from the field to shoot just 41 percent in the first half. Game notes
The Warriors activated guard Bob Sura from the injured list and waived guard Oscar Torres. Sura missed the first 27 games of the season and all of the preseason with a strained right calf and strained lower back. ... The Raptors swept the Warriors last season. ... Murphy had his 12th double-double of the season. ... The Warriors did not give up 100 points for the first time in 10 games. Had they allowed 100 points for the 10th consecutive game, it would have been the longest since giving up 100 in 28 consecutive games to end the 1994-95 season. ... Jamison scored a season-low seven points in 42 minutes.
